    {
        "content": "<p>Instead of using equality of functors, you should be talking about natural isomorphisms of functors (for example using <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CategoryTheory.Limits.diagramIsoPair#doc\">docs#CategoryTheory.Limits.diagramIsoPair</a>). Then you can use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CategoryTheory.Limits.Cones.postcompose#doc\">docs#CategoryTheory.Limits.Cones.postcompose</a> and <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=CategoryTheory.Limits.IsLimit.postcomposeHomEquiv#doc\">docs#CategoryTheory.Limits.IsLimit.postcomposeHomEquiv</a> to translate between cones over one functor and cones over another and to transfer being a limit.</p>",
        "id": 500900854,
        "sender_full_name": "Markus Himmel",
        "timestamp": 1740063689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Alright, I'll give that a try then. Thanks everyone! Just for my own curiosity, I do actually have equal functors, is there still no way to do this?</p>",
